nique  needs.\r\n\r\nAnne is currently employed in a senior academic and administrative  position at the Endeavour College of Natural health where one of her  main roles is to lecture and supervise students of naturopathy. She is  also an experienced presenter of corporate health seminars.\r\n<h2>What is Naturopathy?</h2>\r\nNaturopathy works from within by harnessing your bodyâ€™s own natural healing resources to alleviate illness. A naturopath will not only treat your presenting symptoms but will also endeavour to diagnose and treat the underlying cause of disease. Our approach is holistic. We do not pursue treatment until we have made a thorough investigation into your well-being as an individual. Once we have an understanding of your overall health, we pursue a therapeutic strategy that includes remedies to stimulate and aid the bodyâ€™s resources in recovery as well as to prevent the likelihood of reoccurrence. Naturopathic prescriptions include herbal tinctures, â€œpractitioner onlyâ€ nutritional supplements and herbal products. We also provide counseling on basic diet and lifestyle.\r\n\r\nA core belief of naturopathy is that health is more than just the absence of disease. Health is when all aspects of your mental/emotional, biochemical and physical being are in balance. Our mandate is to make you well. Occasionally, this may mean recognizing the limitations of natural medicine and referring you to orthodox treatment.\r\n\r\nAnother key role of the naturopath is to educate. When you come to us with an illness, we will educate you about your condition and provide information on how to take care of yourself.\r\n<h2>How Can Naturopathy Help You and Your Family?</h2>\r\nNaturopathy offers a broad spectrum of alternative treatments from preventative healthcare through to treatment for serious, chronic debilitating disease. We provide safe and effective therapy for children and adults to manage a range of conditions including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Colds, flu and upper